    en: "New York Criminal Procedure Law Article 190 sets the rules for grand jury proceedings. A grand jury of 23 people (16 required for a quorum; 12 votes needed to indict) meets in secret to hear evidence presented by the prosecution and decide whether there is reasonable cause to believe a felony was committed and the defendant committed it. A felony defendant in New York has the unusual state-law right to testify personally before the grand jury if served with notice and chooses to exercise it (CPL 190.50). Witnesses before the grand jury generally receive transactional immunity for their testimony (CPL 190.40). Grand jury proceedings are secret and disclosure of testimony outside authorized channels is a crime."
